i> Canadian Class 1 pilot and instrument flight engineer Chris		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iGoodfellow wrote an analytical article proposing a theory. He stated		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithat Captain Zaharie's flight maneuvers, in his view, all align with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icharacteristics of an electrical fire. Under this hypothesis, he		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icould understand the purpose of every flight action.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> He speculated that an underinflated front tire or mechanical		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifailure (possibly a ruptured wheel bearing) caused spontaneous		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icombustion during takeoff due to overheating. Unaware of the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ismoldering tire, Zaharie retracted the landing gear, gradually		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iigniting a fire. By the time the pilots realized, communication		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilines and transponders were either burned out or they had to cut		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipower, causing the disappearance. The left turn was key evidence of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ian emergency return maneuver. The subsequent climb to 45,000 feet		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iaimed to reduce oxygen levels and suppress flames. Chris explained		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe sudden plunge as a high-altitude stall, with recovery at 25,000		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifeet.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> Based on radar-confirmed flight paths, Chris believes Zaharie's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itarget was Langkawi International Airport in Malaysia. Its runway		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifaces open sea, allowing unobstructed approach and potential water		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iditching. At 3km long with light traffic, it was closer than Kuala		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLumpur (which required crossing 8,000ft/2,400m mountains). Chris		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iasserts Zaharie, familiar with Langkawi, headed directly there.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> Between ~1:40-2:40, the plane vanished from military radar for an		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihour. From the last radar point to Langkawi is ~100km, aligned with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe runway. The reappearance point was ~130km away, suggesting		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iZaharie circled low over water (below radar coverage) assessing		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilanding options. With tires/landing gear possibly destroyed and no		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iradio contact, a belly landing with full fuel tanks at night was		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ideemed too risky. Zaharie then chose to divert toward the Indian		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOcean, hoping for rescue after ground sightings. He flew low near		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipopulated areas to attract attention—at least four eyewitness		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ireports resulted.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> Finally, needing sufficient fuel to reach Australia, Zaharie		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icontinued. His rationale: 1) Buy time 2) Seek islands for beach		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilandings 3) Enable aerial refueling rescue 4) Worst-case, attempt		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idesert landing in Australia. However, potential navigation failure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iled to crash in the southern Indian Ocean. (Thus, Western Australian		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ideserts should be searched.)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
